---

Voice/call stack:
- Twilio Voice SDK for outbound/inbound calls and media streams.
- Twilio Media Streams (WebSocket) for raw audio delivery to backend.
- OpenAI Whisper API for speech-to-text (STT) transcription.
- OpenAI GPT-4o for real-time analysis (sentiment, guidance, objection handling).
- S3-compatible storage for call recordings.
- Celery workers for post-call deep analysis and deal prediction.

Call pipeline architecture:
- Agent clicks "Call" → Twilio Client SDK initiates call from browser.
- Twilio streams raw audio → Backend Socket.IO/WebSocket handler receives chunks.
- Backend sends audio → Whisper API → transcript chunk returned.
- Backend sends transcript context → GPT-4o → streaming analysis (sentiment, guidance).
- Backend publishes results via Redis Pub/Sub → Socket.IO → Frontend live panel.
- On call end: Twilio webhook → enqueue Celery job → full transcription + deep analysis + deal prediction.

Rules:
- Keep voice pipeline separate from REST API request paths; share lead/call context.
- Transcriptions and summaries must be stored and linked to the call record for history and analytics.
- Do not stream raw audio directly to LLM prompts; use STT first, then text-based analysis.
- Prefer async Celery tasks for recording uploads, full transcription, and summary generation.
- Secure storage and access control for recordings; comply with PII retention policies.
- Audio processing utilities should live in backend/app/utils/audio.py.

Do not:
- Hardcode Twilio or OpenAI API keys; use config/env.
- Store unencrypted call recordings in publicly accessible locations.
- Mix voice-specific business logic with generic lead/CRUD services.
- Block the main API event loop with long-running audio processing.
